06:25.440 --> 06:33.320
This is Daryl Lane. And David Carson. No other field has fans as distinctive and
intense, some would even say as fanatical, as science fiction does. Every year

06:33.320 --> 06:40.000
there are hundreds of conventions around the country, from small local affairs
to the Incredible World Convention, at which fans gather. They come for various

06:40.000 --> 06:47.480
reasons, of course. To socialize with like-minded people, to meet science
fiction and fantasy authors, to buy books at the dealer's tables. There's one

06:47.480 --> 06:55.340
particular type of fan with a special, consuming interest, costuming and
masquerade. Most conventions, therefore, have a masquerade section, a contest

06:55.340 --> 07:02.740
for fans who have made and presented a costume from some science fiction or
fantasy work. The Science Fiction Radio Show spoke with Teresa Patterson, a fan

07:02.740 --> 07:09.660
who has won numerous awards for her science fiction and fantasy costuming. She
says a few years ago she was hooked on Star Trek, but do nothing about fandom.

07:10.220 --> 07:18.280
But one day after Star Trek, there was a big advertisement for a Star Trek
convention in Dallas. And it was going to have some of the stars there and

07:18.280 --> 07:28.180
everything, and I'd never heard of such a thing. But it sounded like a lot of
fun, so we went down, and then I ran into nearly 1,500 to 2,000 fans who also

07:28.180 --> 07:38.120
liked Star Trek, who also had a reason for coming to science fiction and
fantasy, and had been touched by Star Trek because of this feeling they had. And

07:38.120 --> 07:46.360
all of a sudden I had a family and a place to belong. And I've been an avid fan
ever since, going to as many conventions as I could. And one aspect of this

07:46.360 --> 07:54.420
convention was costuming. And I'd always been sort of interested in theater and
that sort of thing, but never really involved. But here were all these people

07:54.420 --> 08:01.520
who weren't really into theater and weren't performers, but they had all these
wonderful costumes and were going up and doing the masquerades. The next time

08:01.520 --> 08:11.640
they had a convention, I was ready, and I had my first costume. It was a very
poorly made Mirror Mirror costume from the Star Trek episode Mirror Mirror. But

08:11.640 --> 08:20.220
it was a beginning, and it was something, and all of a sudden I was involved,
and I had a part in a world where in my main life I didn't have much of anything

08:20.220 --> 08:30.860
that I really belonged to. And through fandom and science fiction and belonging
to that world, I eventually learned how to belong in a normal world again. And

08:30.860 --> 08:39.780
basically, it changed my entire life. I actually even became popular in high
school, which at the time that I started in fandom, I would have thought that

08:39.780 --> 08:50.620
popularity was something I would never see. So, and then it grew from there. I
became a theater and drama major at UTA, and I now work as a professional singer

08:50.620 --> 09:00.700
and performer and do a lot of costuming with that job and freelance costuming.
But my first love is still making characters come alive on the stage at science

09:00.700 --> 09:08.260
fiction and fantasy conventions. Because I think that what I was searching for
at the time was a reality that I could fit into, and I think that's what the

09:08.260 --> 09:13.780
other fans are searching for. And the masquerade gives me a chance to make that
dream become a reality.

09:24.460 --> 09:32.300
We asked her to give us an example of bringing a science fiction character to
life through costuming. One of our most successful costume skits that we

09:32.300 --> 09:42.580
designed, and I had some other people with me at the time, we went to Worldcon
in Boston, and we had a young fellow who was a good friend of mine and my little

09:42.580 --> 09:52.720
sister did a Star Wars skit together. But what they did was the lights darkened
and the Star Wars theme came up, and all of a sudden, Luke Skywalker came flying

09:52.720 --> 10:03.840
through the air doing somersaults onto the stage, stopped and did a one-handed
handstand, very precariously balancing, using the Force to hold him up. And then

10:03.840 --> 10:12.020
Yoda came slowly onto stage, nodding wisely, and instructing him on the use of
the Force. He didn't get it right the first time, then he tried again the second

10:12.020 --> 10:20.980
time, and finally succeeded with a perfect one-handed handstand, balancing with
the use of the Force. And then leapt up, did a couple more flying leaps and

10:20.980 --> 10:30.780
somersaults in the middle of the air across the stage and left. standing ovation
by 9,000 screaming people who, for them, Star Wars was alive. We'll talk with

10:30.780 --> 10:33.300
Teresa Patterson about fans and costuming next time.

