17:39.740 --> 17:44.620
Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

17:47.180 --> 17:48.980
And here are your hosts.

17:52.920 --> 17:59.980
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. Teresa Patterson is a science fiction
fantasy fan who was turned on by the idea of making familiar characters from the

17:59.980 --> 18:07.200
field come to life for others. She goes to science fiction conventions with
carefully constructed costumes and colorful skits. She enters the masquerade or

18:07.200 --> 18:14.540
some costuming competition with her creations and has won many awards. Costuming
is a fascinating part of science fiction fandom. We observed that there must be

18:14.540 --> 18:25.460
some acting ability that goes along with it. Of course. But actually, I think
there's a bit of actress or actor in almost everyone who's into the fandom scene

18:25.460 --> 18:34.320
at all and even people who aren't. It's just a matter of whether we can actually
do something with it or not. A lot of people just assume, well, that'll never

18:34.320 --> 18:40.400
happen. I'll never get to do anything with it and they forget about that part of
their personality. I'm a little more stubborn. I intend to do it professionally

18:40.400 --> 18:51.260
eventually and to some extent am doing that now with my performing as a singer
and dancer with the singing telegram companies and as a model and so forth. And

18:51.260 --> 19:00.700
I've been in two science fiction movies as an extra, Logan's Run and Lathe of
Heaven, which both were a lot of fun. But it doesn't take an actor or an actress

19:00.700 --> 19:09.700
to do these kind of things and I've seen a lot of really wonderful skits and
costumes and performances pulled off by people who had never even considered the

19:09.700 --> 19:17.800
idea of being professional actors or actresses. They just want to make it real.
And that's all acting ever was, was just trying to make something real and

19:17.800 --> 19:25.880
recreate something. It's just that what we do is a little different than your
typical stage play. But it should be no less entertaining and we're trying to

19:25.880 --> 19:33.180
create it so that it's no less entertaining. Patterson usually works with a
group of friends in performing her masquerade skits who wondered how newcomers

19:33.180 --> 19:41.940
took to costuming. Do they become converts fairly quickly? We don't have anyone
who's ever met or joined our group that hasn't immediately ended up in a

19:41.940 --> 19:53.100
costume. Sometimes under protest the first time but they always end up under a
costume and then they always want more and more costumes and the next thing you

19:53.100 --> 20:02.880
know we've got a whole new set of costumers. When we went to Boston we took five
people in four different costume skits. These five people I was the only one

20:02.880 --> 20:10.180
who'd ever been to a WorldCon before. Most of them had never even been to a
major convention before. All they knew was they wanted to do the masquerade.

20:10.360 --> 20:17.580
They loved science fiction and fantasy and fandom and they wanted to do the
masquerade and they had a lot of creativity and they were willing to listen to

20:17.580 --> 20:27.200
suggestions and we all worked together and we came away with four awards. People
who nobody had ever heard of before we went up there to the WorldCon and won

20:27.200 --> 20:37.120
four of the top awards. Best Presentation Overall, First Runner-Up for Best
Presentation, Star Wars Special Award Prize and First Runner-Up for Best

20:37.120 --> 20:37.540
Fantasy.

20:45.280 --> 20:51.580
We asked Patterson how she taught herself to do the elaborate costuming she's
doing now. I still don't know what I'm doing now.

20:54.580 --> 21:04.500
I've learned a lot from other people and from lots of trial and error, mostly
trial and error. I discovered fabric glue when I was in desperation and it works

21:04.500 --> 21:14.880
wonderfully on all kinds of things. When I started costuming, I really didn't
know anything about sewing at all. The idea of making clothes was the farthest

21:14.880 --> 21:22.260
thing from my mind and it just happened that I needed a costume and I had to
figure out how to create this thing that you couldn't possibly buy in a store by

21:22.260 --> 21:31.160
its very nature and the first costumes were very much trial and error but since
then, I've learned a lot of shortcuts, shortcuts that an average seamstress

21:31.160 --> 21:39.560
would probably never use because they learned all the rules and I didn't and I
try to pass on those shortcuts and at a lot of the major conventions, they have

21:39.560 --> 21:48.560
workshops where they discuss costuming and shortcuts that other people have
found and stage techniques and there are books and magazines out that cover

21:48.560 --> 21:57.580
costuming and makeup and easy ways to do all these things. Any fan who's seen
some of Teresa Patterson's work can't help but be impressed. She's made many

21:57.580 --> 22:02.880
characters from fantasy and science fiction live. We'll talk about some other
aspects of fandom on our next show.

