23:37.740 --> 23:45.480
This is David Carson and Daryl Lane. This will be our final show with Teresa
Patterson, science fiction fan and costume designer. Patterson talks about the

23:45.480 --> 23:54.100
various types of science fiction fans. And our listeners should keep in mind
that in fan terminology, fin is the plural of fan. There are actually several

23:54.100 --> 24:04.020
different level of fans. There are new fin, which are people who just discovered
that, oh, you mean there's somebody else that reads this stuff besides me? There

24:04.020 --> 24:14.640
are true fin, who are the people who go to conventions on a live and die
situation and fandom is a way of life and will sell whatever they can sell at

24:14.640 --> 24:23.920
the dealers' tables if they can make enough money to get back and forth between
the conventions and who literally, the convention society, is their social life.

24:24.100 --> 24:32.580
Then there are a whole scope of people in between. There are what we call closet
fans who are the people who read the books, who watch the shows, who go to the

24:32.580 --> 24:42.160
movies, but who have absolutely no idea that there's any kind of organization
out there whatsoever. There are the slightly organized fans, which are people

24:42.160 --> 24:49.980
who realize that there is organization who maybe go to a con every now and then,
who every now and then get a chance to meet their favorite author, but who

24:49.980 --> 24:55.700
really aren't that much into the convention scene. It's just something that they
like and every now and then they like to express the fact that they enjoy it.

24:55.960 --> 25:03.720
And then, of course, there are the professional fin, which are people who
through their professions one way or the other have somehow gotten tied up with

25:03.720 --> 25:12.140
the science fiction or fantasy genre and because they deal with it every day or
part of every day and because they must like it or they wouldn't deal with it to

25:12.140 --> 25:13.540
some extent. They're fin too.

25:20.140 --> 25:27.280
Serious science fiction fans who attend conventions live in a weird sort of
world with its own activities and even its own vocabulary. Both these aspects of

25:27.280 --> 25:36.260
fandom are illustrated in the word folk singing. We asked Patterson to explain
it to us. Well, basically, like any other, when you take fandom as a microcosm

25:36.260 --> 25:47.380
of people and that this is their social life when they're at a convention, you
have to deal with the fact that social life includes entertainment. And if

25:47.380 --> 25:53.900
you're into science fiction and fantasy and you're doing something special like
a convention, you don't want to go out and entertain yourself by going to the

25:53.900 --> 26:02.640
local bar or the local disco. That's boring. You want to do something that's
uniquely fandom. And so something that was developed through fandom is a thing

26:02.640 --> 26:15.680
called filk singing. Filk singing is folk singing, sort of. Basically, filk
singing is a creation of songs that are performed by one person or many person

26:15.680 --> 26:26.520
on or off key, it makes no difference, that were written specifically for the
audience of science fiction and fantasy listeners. Patterson says there can be

26:26.520 --> 26:35.440
different kinds of filk singing, but that they all fulfill a need among science
fiction fans. Now, some of filk singing is very simple. It simply involves

26:35.440 --> 26:44.620
taking a tune from a normal song and changing the words around to have something
to do with science fiction or fantasy, and usually those are funny and they're

26:44.620 --> 26:53.500
the kind that you can get a lot of giggles off and everyone joins in. But the
more serious element is original songs that deal with very serious ideas like

26:53.500 --> 27:03.260
the fact that man's finally reaching for space and the Columbia's here or the
fact that when are we really going to get to be dancing on the moon by the time

27:03.260 --> 27:16.040
it actually happens I'll be too old and things like that. And filking is a whole
type of folk singing strictly for fans. And some fans don't like it because they

27:16.040 --> 27:24.360
don't like the taking of other people's music and putting other lyrics to it.
But for most fans, it's a wonderful outlet for getting to know other people and

27:24.360 --> 27:33.440
just sit around at night when there's nothing else to do and sing songs and get
a very close type of camaraderie that you only get in some other kind of very

27:33.440 --> 27:43.240
close-knit group. Not all conventions have filk singing but the more intimate
ones where it really is a social life type situation do because it's a very big

27:43.240 --> 27:49.540
part of the social life. Patterson's enthusiasm for science fiction and science
fiction fandom is obvious and infectious.

